Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): SLE is an autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the skin, joints, kidneys, and blood. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, nasal ulcers, and malar rash.
Antiphospholipid syndrome (APS): APS is an autoimmune disease that causes the blood to clot too easily. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, and skin rash.

Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP): TTP is a rare blood disorder that causes blood clots to form in small blood vessels throughout the body. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, and neurological problems.
Hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS): HUS is a rare kidney disorder that is often caused by an infection. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, and kidney failure.
Sepsis: Sepsis is a serious infection that can cause widespread inflammation and organ damage. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, and fever.

Meningitis: Meningitis is an inflammation of the lining of the brain and spinal cord. It can be caused by a variety of infections, including bacteria, viruses, and fungi. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, headache, stiff neck, and rash.

Encephalitis: Encephalitis is an inflammation of the brain. It can be caused by a variety of infections, including viruses, bacteria, and parasites. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, headache, confusion, and seizures.

Guillain-Barre syndrome: Guillain-Barre syndrome is a rare disorder in which the bodys immune system attacks the nerves. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including muscle weakness, numbness, and tingling.

Myasthenia gravis: Myasthenia gravis is a rare autoimmune disease that causes muscle weakness. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including drooping eyelids, difficulty swallowing, and muscle weakness.
